This paper deals with the problem of path computation for dynamic service provisioning in transport networks, which is a topic related to network infrastructure (NI) and network protocols (NP). The use of on-line algorithms and the creation of an auxiliary graph structure suggest a focus on data structures and algorithms (DS). The consideration of different topologies and layers in the network suggests a focus on robotics (RO) and systems and control (SI). Finally, the use of weight assignment schemes and dynamic weight functions suggests a focus on information theory (IT).
